data.content:
## C# 14 Span Overload Resolution Change

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` on `int[]` to resolve to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this fails at runtime.

### Fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast in the expression
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains<int>`, which is expression-tree compatible. The same issue can affect `Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` there too.
